I'it. XXVIII. Obligatio in this Title means a right arising ex con- tractu: it tells us who takes the benefit of a contract made by a filius· familias, slave, or free man bona fide serviens: cf. Tit. 17 supr. The converse question, how far the superioris bound by their promises, is treated in Bk iv. 7 inf.

For the ‘divisio rerum proprietatis et ususfructus’ see on Bk ii. 9. pr. supr. The commodum an'sing from the contracts of a filiusfamilias was not necessarily divided in this manner. lf he had only castrense or quasi-castrense peculium, the commodum was all his own, and on such contracts he could sue in person, Dig. ¹4· 6. 2 ε 49. 17. 41, ib. 5: Cod. 6 8. pr.-2. lf his peculium was profectitium only, it was all the father’s; if hehad adventitium as well, the father had a usufruct in the commodum obligationis in the ratio which it bore to the other peculia ‘quae adqui- sitionem effugiunt' Cod. 6. 61. 6.
